# Builder and Repository Patterns

## Use builders for DynamoDB key construction

Don't inline key construction in business logic. Delegate to a builder:

```ts
// Bad
const key = {
  primaryKey: userId,
  'category#type': `${PreferenceStoreCategoryType.Purpose}#${purpose}`,
};

// Good
const key = PurposeRecordBuilder.build({ userId, purpose });
```

## Repository pattern for data access

Business logic should speak the language of the domain, not DynamoDB:

```ts
// Bad — business logic knows about DynamoDB structure
const items = await table.query({
  KeyConditionExpression: 'primaryKey = :pk',
  ExpressionAttributeValues: { ':pk': userId },
});
const purposes = items.map(item => /* manual mapping */);

// Good — business logic speaks domain language
const purposes = await consentRepository.getPurposeConsents(userId);
```

## Domain aggregates and value objects

When introducing new concepts, make them explicit types with behavior:

```ts
// Value object pattern
class LinkedIdentifier {
  constructor(
    readonly name: string,
    readonly value: string,
    readonly scope: 'unique' | 'shared',
  ) {}

  static fromStorageKey(raw: string): LinkedIdentifier {
    // parsing logic in ONE place
  }

  toStorageKey(): string { /* ... */ }
}
```

## Keep storage shapes at the edge

io-ts / zod codecs validate at DynamoDB/API boundaries. They should not be passed through service layers. Map to domain types immediately after validation:

```ts
// At the boundary
const raw = ConsentPreferencesByCategoryCodec.decode(dbItem);
// Immediately map to domain type
const record = ConsentRecord.fromStorage(raw);
// Business logic only sees ConsentRecord
```
